<br>
Example:<br>
<br>
A McDonalds has the same relative prices as a Burger King 300 miles away.  Are they in direct competition?<br>
<br>
  Obvious answer:  No<br>
<br>
Are the prices of the McDonalds competitive with that Burger King and the rest of the food industry?<br>
<br>
  Obvious answer:  Yes<br>
<br>
I personally don't know if KBR's prices are competitive with their industry, but I am intelligent enough to know when the prices for services provided are competitive to their industry or $21,000.00 toilet seats.<br>
<br>
  Are you denying that a company can provide competitive services without a bidding process? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=anywon>Anywon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I can't decide on a title</span><br>  Posts: 900<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/2/03 5:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=215.topic&index=41>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> competitive prices</span><hr size=1> McDonalds and Burger King offer the similar products in a highly competitive, fairly uniform market.<br>
<br>
Haliburton's services are, by comparison, limited to a fairly small subset of a vertical market.<br>
<br>
How many oil rig fires are there a year?<br>
<br>
How many temporary air strips are build a year?<br>
<br>
The cost of a toilet seat could very well be justified at $500 if there are other mitigating factors involved.  i.e. Is the toilet seat installed on a B-52 bomber and must be manufactured with predefined Military Specifications (MILSPEC).  The competitive market price for a hammer could very well be $1200 if it is a specialized hammer with a specific use.  Simply pointing to invoices with those items listed would not prove the allegations.<br>
<br>
Without a competitive bidding process, it is difficult to argue one way or the other whether or not the costs were too high.  A market has not been established for the types of work given in the no-bid contracts.  That subjects the &quot;competitive&quot; requirement of the compelling evidence to extreme variations in interpretation.<br>
<br>
The argument you are using, where you cite common-known costs for general purpose materials and services, was shown to be completely misleading when that type of GAO accounting scandal was in the public spotlight 20 years ago.<br>
<br>
Fair prices in one market do not equate to fair prices in a dissimilar market.<br>
<br>
That is why there is an Open Bid process.<br>
<br>
That is why the No-Bid contracts are drawing a high level of scrutiny and criticism. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 2164<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/2/03 8:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=215.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: competitive prices</span><hr size=1> If you look at my post, I specify that if there is reason to believe that the situation has changed and the pricing is no longer valid, then another source must be found or a bidding system must be used.<br>
<br>
I agree with you that sometimes situations change and circumstances change.  However, they don't always.  Just because a market is unfamiliar to me (such as the oil market) doesn't mean that there are no established prices.<br>
